{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5182,"record_hash":"sha256:1b905fab17e84bee7bf9b5e2a373b58394af7b278ac63cb026158efed0c6515b","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:26:52.703Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:291-295) [added]\n[P1] Slash-leading secrets can bypass redaction\n\n`is_obvious_path()` treats any candidate starting with `/` as an obvious path when it lacks `+` or `=`, even outside path-like fields. A slash-leading token such as `[REDACTED:entropy]` in message text or an `api_key` value is high-entropy and candidate-shaped, but will be stored verbatim. The path exemption should probably require path-like field context or a stronger path shape.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:121-127) [added]\n[P2] Sensitive field names do not force redaction\n\n`field_name` currently only feeds exemptions, so obvious sensitive keys still rely on entropy/length/UUID shape. Low-entropy passwords, UUID-shaped API keys, or other structured secrets under names like `password`, `token`, `api_key`, or `authorization` can be stored with `source_record_redacted=false`. A small denylist before the exemptions would close this without adding a scanner framework.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:406-431) [added]\n[P3] Broad SHA labels preserve non-Git hex\n\nLabels like `sha`, `sha1`, and `sha256` are not Git-specific. A 40/64-character hex token under a `sha256` field or after `sha256:` is preserved even though the POC says clearly Git-labelled object IDs should survive. Tightening this to Git-ish labels such as `commit_sha`, `object_id`, `tree`, `blob`, and `parent` would make the exception more honest.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nOkay lets address Slash-leading secrets can bypass redaction \n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:26:52.703Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:291-295) [added]\n[P1] Slash-leading secrets can bypass redaction\n\n`is_obvious_path()` treats any candidate starting with `/` as an obvious path when it lacks `+` or `=`, even outside path-like fields. A slash-leading token such as `[REDACTED:entropy]` in message text or an `api_key` value is high-entropy and candidate-shaped, but will be stored verbatim. The path exemption should probably require path-like field context or a stronger path shape.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:121-127) [added]\n[P2] Sensitive field names do not force redaction\n\n`field_name` currently only feeds exemptions, so obvious sensitive keys still rely on entropy/length/UUID shape. Low-entropy passwords, UUID-shaped API keys, or other structured secrets under names like `password`, `token`, `api_key`, or `authorization` can be stored with `source_record_redacted=false`. A small denylist before the exemptions would close this without adding a scanner framework.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:406-431) [added]\n[P3] Broad SHA labels preserve non-Git hex\n\nLabels like `sha`, `sha1`, and `sha256` are not Git-specific. A 40/64-character hex token under a `sha256` field or after `sha256:` is preserved even though the POC says clearly Git-labelled object IDs should survive. Tightening this to Git-ish labels such as `commit_sha`, `object_id`, `tree`, `blob`, and `parent` would make the exception more honest.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nOkay lets address Slash-leading secrets can bypass redaction \n"}]}}}